🧠 Machine Learning Models — Types, Uses & Examples

Machine learning models are broadly grouped into three main types based on the kind of task they solve:

Type    ->      Goal    ->  	Example ->   Problems   -> 	Typical Output
Supervised Learning	    ->      Predict a target (label)    ->      Classification, Regression      ->      Numeric or Category
Unsupervised Learning	->      Find hidden patterns        ->  	Clustering, Dimensionality Reduction	->  Groups, Structures
Reinforcement Learning	->      Optimize decision-making	->      Trading, Robotics, Games	->      Actions, Policies

Let’s focus on the supervised and unsupervised models (the most relevant for data analysts, data scientists, and product/finance analytics).

🏷️ 1. Classification Models

→ Goal: Predict discrete labels (e.g., “yes/no”, “category”, “segment”).

Model		->      Core Idea		->      When to Use	Example Use Cases
Logistic Regression		->      Estimates probability of class using a sigmoid function		->      Binary classification, simple interpretable models		->      Credit risk (default / no default), customer churn prediction
Decision Tree		->      Splits data into regions using feature thresholds		->      When interpretability is important		->      Fraud detection, loan approval logic
Random Forest		->      Ensemble of multiple decision trees (bagging)		->      High accuracy, low overfitting		->      Predict business unit, customer segmentation
Gradient Boosting / XGBoost / LightGBM / CatBoost		->      Builds trees sequentially to correct previous errors		->      Structured/tabular data; high accuracy		->      Marketing response prediction, revenue forecasting
Support Vector Machine (SVM)		->      Finds optimal boundary between classes		->      When you have few samples and clear separation		->      Image/text classification
K-Nearest Neighbors (KNN)		->      Classifies based on neighbors’ labels		->      Small datasets, non-linear boundaries		->      Product recommendation, anomaly detection
Naive Bayes		->      Uses probability and Bayes’ theorem; assumes independence		->      Text and document classification		->      Spam detection, sentiment analysis
Neural Networks (ANN)		->      Multiple connected layers learn complex non-linear relationships		->      Complex or large datasets		->      Image recognition, speech classification

📈 2. Regression Models

→ Goal: Predict continuous numeric values (e.g., price, revenue, yield).

Model		->      Core Idea		->      When to Use 	->      	Example Use Cases
Linear Regression		->      Fits a straight line to minimize error		->      When relationships are mostly linear		->      Predict profit, cost, or salary
Ridge / Lasso Regression		->      Adds penalties to reduce overfitting		->      Many correlated features		->      Risk scoring, demand forecasting
Decision Tree Regressor		->      Splits data for regression tasks		->      Non-linear data	Forecasting 	->      business KPIs
Random Forest Regressor		->      Averages multiple trees	Non-linear + robust model		->      Predicting asset prices, real estate values
Gradient Boosting Regressor / XGBoost		->      Sequential improvement of weak learners		->      High-performance regression 	->      	Forecasting portfolio returns
Support Vector Regression (SVR)	SVM for continuous targets		->      Non-linear regression		->      Pricing optimization
Neural Networks (for regression)	->      	Multi-layer models		->      Complex relationships		->      Predicting sales, temperature, energy usage

🧩 3. Unsupervised Learning Models

→ Goal: No target label; find patterns or structure.

Model		->      Core Idea		->      When to Use		->      Example Use Cases
K-Means Clustering		->      Groups data into K clusters based on similarity		->      Market segmentation	Customer segmentation by behavior
Hierarchical Clustering	Builds 	->      tree-like clusters		->      Exploratory analysis		->      Grouping fund performance profiles
DBSCAN		->      Density-based clustering		->      Uneven cluster shapes		->      Fraud or anomaly detection
Principal Component Analysis (PCA)		->      Reduces dimensionality by combining correlated features		->      Feature reduction, visualization		->      Portfolio factor analysis, risk modeling
Autoencoders		->      Neural network for unsupervised feature extraction	->      	Complex data compression		->      Anomaly detection, dimensionality reduction

🔁 4. Time Series & Forecasting Models

→ Goal: Predict values that change over time.

Model		->      Core Idea		->      When to Use	Example 	->       Use Cases
ARIMA / SARIMA		->      Autoregressive moving average models		->      Stationary or seasonal data		->      Forecast revenue, demand, or stock prices
Prophet (by Meta)		->      Decomposes trend, seasonality, holidays 	->      	Business forecasting		->      Forecasting sales, bookings
LSTM / GRU (Neural Networks)		->      Sequential learning		->      Long-term dependencies in time series	->      	Financial time series, demand forecasting

🧮 5. Ensemble Methods (Combine multiple models)
Method		->      Description		->      Why use it
Bagging (Bootstrap Aggregating)	Trains multiple models on random subsets (e.g., Random Forest)	Reduces variance (less overfitting)
Boosting		->      Sequentially trains models to correct errors (e.g., XGBoost, LightGBM)		->      Reduces bias and improves accuracy
Stacking		->      Combines predictions from multiple models		->      Builds stronger “meta-model”

🏦 Example Mapping for Your Use Case (Banking / Ledger / Treasury)
Problem Type	Example	Suitable Models
Classification	Predict business unit from ledger attributes	Random Forest, XGBoost, Decision Tree
Regression	Predict loan default probability / interest margin	Linear Regression, XGBoost Regressor
Anomaly Detection	Detect unusual trades / ledger movements	Isolation Forest, One-Class SVM
Clustering	Segment client accounts / transactions	K-Means, DBSCAN
Forecasting	Forecast liquidity / balance / P&L	ARIMA, Prophet, LSTM

🚀 Key Takeaways

Choose classification if your target is a label/category.

Choose regression if your target is a number.

Choose clustering if there’s no target but you want to find groups.

Use ensemble models (Random Forest, XGBoost) for best accuracy on structured data.

Use deep learning (Neural Nets, LSTM) for complex, high-dimensional, or unstructured data.




⭐ 1. CRNN — Convolutional Recurrent Neural Network

This is the most common modern OCR model.

Architecture:
CNN → feature extraction
RNN (Bi-LSTM) → sequence modeling
CTC (Connectionist Temporal Classification) → text decoding


Used in:

Tesseract 4+

PaddleOCR

EasyOCR

Google OCR models

CRNN is excellent for:

Printed text

Handwriting

Cursive writing

Irregular spacing

Full-line OCR

⭐ 2. Transformer-based OCR (Best current method)

Transformers (like those used in GPT-4) are now state of the art.

Examples:

Google Vision OCR (Transformers)

TrOCR (Microsoft)

Donut (OCR-free document understanding)

Benefits:

Handles entire documents

Strong on messy real-world scans

Better handling of layout, paragraphs, tables

Transformers outperform CNN-based OCR in most cases today.